[Epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD) is the most important disease of
white-tailed deer. Outbreaks are common in the Southeastern USA, but
they are also frequently documented further north. The disease is
transmitted by biting midges and its occurrence is seasonal. The
die-offs cease with the 1st frosts. The EHD virus does not pose a risk
for human or livestock health. High density deer herds may have higher
mortality rates; however, the relationship of deer density to the
severity of hemorrhagic disease is not clear-cut, as the virus is not
spread by direct contact and depends on the dynamics of the arthropod
vector. For more information on the disease see comments in
ProMED-mail post 20110918.2842. - Mod.PMB]

[The state of Michigan can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/1iS-. Cass and St Joseph
counties in southwestern Michigan can be seen on the map at
http://www.digital-topo-maps.com/county-map/michigan.shtml. -
Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
